<BaseLayout title="Research" description="Agreni Batra's research on equitable STEM learning, curriculum design, and teacher preparation.">
  <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 py-14">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-serif font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-6">Research</h1>

    <!-- PLACEHOLDER: Replace with real research description before launch -->
    <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-10">
      My research examines the conditions under which students from historically marginalized
      communities develop rigorous scientific and mathematical thinking. I am particularly
      interested in the design of learning environments that honor the knowledge students bring
      and that position all students — regardless of prior achievement, language background, or
      socioeconomic context — as capable of deep disciplinary reasoning. The three areas below
      represent the current shape of this work, though they are deeply intertwined in practice.
    </p>

    <!-- Research interest 1 -->
    <section class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-serif font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">
        Equitable STEM Learning Environments
      </h2>
      <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
        <!-- PLACEHOLDER: Replace with real research interest description -->
        What structural, pedagogical, and relational conditions make it possible for all students
        to engage as genuine scientific thinkers? This strand of my work draws on classroom
        observation, interview, and design-based research to understand how teachers and curriculum
        developers can build learning environments that distribute participation and intellectual
        authority more equitably. It attends especially to contexts where students carry significant
        out-of-school stressors and where instructional time is constrained.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Research interest 2 -->
    <section class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-serif font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">
        Curriculum Design &amp; Inquiry-Based Pedagogy
      </h2>
      <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
        <!-- PLACEHOLDER: Replace with real research interest description -->
        Curriculum is a medium for enacting values — and the detailed choices made in its design
        profoundly shape what counts as knowledge and who is positioned as a knower. This strand
        examines how asset-oriented, inquiry-based curriculum can be designed, implemented, and
        iteratively refined in partnership with teachers. It includes work on task design,
        sequencing, and the development of materials that give teachers principled flexibility
        rather than scripted compliance.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Research interest 3 -->
    <section class="mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-serif font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-3">
        Teacher Preparation &amp; Professional Learning
      </h2>
      <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
        <!-- PLACEHOLDER: Replace with real research interest description -->
        Shifting classroom practice at scale requires sustained, practice-embedded professional
        learning — not one-time workshops. This strand of my work explores what teacher preparation
        and ongoing professional development must look like to support educators who are building
        inquiry-based, equity-centered classrooms. It draws on my experience with the Teach For
        India network and informs current work with teacher preparation programs and out-of-school
        STEM programming in New York City.
      </p>
    </section>

    <p class="text-sm text-slate-500 italic mt-8">
      All content on this page is placeholder text. Publications, projects, and affiliations will be added before launch.
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
